    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1967-02-18T12:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1967-02-18T12:30:00-05:00" n="201"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d201">
                <head>201. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in the Soviet Union</gloss>
                    to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d201fn1">Source: National Archives and Records
                        Administration, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files,
                        1967–69, POL <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_USSR1"
                            >USSR</gloss>. Secret; Immediate; <gloss target="#t_Nodis1"
                            >Nodis</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Moscow</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1967-02-18T17:30:00+00:00">February 18, 1967,
                        1730Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3559. 1. My call on <persName corresp="#p_KAN1">Kosygin</persName> ten a.m. this
                    morning lasted two hours and ten minutes. In addition to Vietnam, which took
                    bulk of time, other subjects discussed were <gloss target="#t_ABM1"
                    >ABM</gloss>s, Soviet agriculture and industry, and <pb facs="0487" n="459"
                        xml:id="pg_459"/> some bilateral matters, all of which being reported in
                        <gloss target="#t_septel1">septel</gloss>s.<note n="2" xml:id="d201fn2">All
                        dated February 18. Telegram 3562, which reported on Vietnam, is printed in
                            <ref target="frus1964-68v05#d85">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations,</hi> 1964–1968, vol. V, Document
                            85</ref>. The text of telegram 3560, which reported on <gloss
                            target="#t_ABM1">ABM</gloss>s, is <ref target="frus1964-68v11#d182"
                            >ibid., vol. XI, Document 182</ref>. Telegram 3565, which reported on
                        Soviet agriculture and industry, is at the National Archives and Records
                        Administration, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1967–69,
                        POL <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>.
                        For reports on bilateral issues, see <ref target="#d202">Documents 202</ref>
                        and <ref target="#d203">203</ref>. Telegram 3561 summarized the discussion
                        of a leased line to improve communication facilities between the Moscow
                        Embassy and Washington. (Johnson Library, National Security File, Country
                        File, <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>, Moscow Embassy Communications
                        Problems) Copies of <persName corresp="#p_TLE1">Thompson</persName>’s
                        telegrams were forwarded to President <persName corresp="#p_JLB1"
                            >Johnson</persName> on November 18. (Memorandum from <persName
                            corresp="#p_RWW1">Rostow</persName> to the President, February 18;
                        ibid., Vol. XIV)</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KAN1">Kosygin</persName> was accompanied by <persName
                        corresp="#p_KGM1">Kornienko</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_TOA1"
                        >Troyanovsky</persName>, and interpreter. I had <persName corresp="#p_AA1"
                        >Akalovsky</persName> with me.</p>
                <p>2. Atmosphere during meeting was very businesslike, with <persName
                        corresp="#p_KAN1">Kosygin</persName> stressing Soviet desire for relaxation
                    of tensions in general and improved <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>-Soviet
                    relations in particular. One thing that struck me especially is <persName
                        corresp="#p_KAN1">Kosygin</persName>’s obvious preoccupation with China.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TLE1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Thompson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
